{"cursor":"3810","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n]]\n\n'Zeng Gong' (, 1019â1083), courtesy name 'Zigu' (å­åº), was a Chinese scholar and\nhistorian of the Song Dynasty in China. He was one of the supporters of the New\nClassical Prose Movement (æ°å¤æéå) and is regarded as founder of one of the Eight\nGreat Schools of Thought of the Tang and Song dynasties (åå®å«å¤§å®¶).\n\nZeng Gong was born in Jianchang (å»ºæ, modern Fuzhou, Jiangxi). He is said to have\nwritten [[Liulun]] å­è« (\"Six arguments\") when he was only twelve. After the work\nwas praised by Ouyang Xiu, one of the intellectual leaders of the era, Zeng Gong\nbecame widely known among literary circles.\n\nIn 1037, at the age of eighteen, he moved to Yushan county (çå±±ç¸£, in modern\nShangrao, Jiangxi) to accompany his father Zeng Yizhan (æ¾æå ), who had been\nappointed magistrate there. Whilst in Yushan, he travelled extensively in its\nhinterlands and wrote [[You Xinzhou Yushan Xiaoyan Ji]] (éä¿¡å·çå±±å°å²©è¨). The work was\ndivided into five sections. The first describes the geography of Yushan,\nfollowed by sections on the caves, rocks etc. Zeng's youthful descriptions show\nhis vivid imagination and literary talent. In his twenties, Zeng Gong travelled\nwidely throughout China, befriending the would be reformer Wang Anshi and later\nrecommending him to Ouyang Xiu.\n\nIn 1057, Zeng Gong achieved the degree of [[Jinshi (imperial\nexamination)|jinshi]] and was appointed to a military post in the provinces. The\nnext year, he was recalled to the capital and served within the department of\nhistory - collecting and drafting documents. From 1069, he was appointed\nsuccessively as the head of Qizhou (é½å·), Xiangzhou (è¥å·), Hongzhou, Fuzhou,\nMingzhou (æå·) and Haozhou.\n\nIn 1080, en route to a fresh appointment in Cangzhou, Zeng was granted an\naudience with Emperor Shenzong. The emperor was suitably impressed and allowed\nZeng to stay at the capital to work on a history of the Five Dynasties period.\nZeng Gong was promoted to become Aide to the Master of Writings (ä¸­æ¸èäºº) in 1082.\nHe died the next year in Jiangning. The new monarch Emperor Lizong granted him\nthe posthumous appellation of \"Wending\" (æå®).\n\nZeng Gong produced some four hundred poems in his lifetime and a number of\nessays. His style of prose writing is mostly discursive rather than\nargumentative. In terms of political philosophy, Zeng was a firm follower of\nOuyang Xiu. For this reason his reputation as leader of one of the eight great\nschools of philosophy has largely been overshadowed by that of his mentor.\nAmong Zeng Gong's collected works are fifty chapters of Yuanfeng Leigao (åè±é¡ç¨¿),\nforty chapters of the Xu Yuanfeng Leigao (çºåè±é¡ç¨¿) and thirty chapters of the\nLongping Ji (éå¹³é).\n\n{{Persondata \n| NAME = Zeng, Gong ALTERNATIVE NAMES = SHORT DESCRIPTION = Chinese historian\n| DATE OF BIRTH = 1019 PLACE OF BIRTH = Fuzhou, Jiangxi, China DATE OF DEATH =\n| 1083 PLACE OF DEATH = Jiangning, China\n}}\n","linknr":133,"url":"Zeng_Gong","recorded":1375066230,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Zeng_Gong&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Zeng_Gong&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.w